        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-06-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-06-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="77"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                <head>77. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d77fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 18, Evening Reports
                        (State): 6/77. Secret. In the upper right-hand corner of the first page of
                        the memorandum, <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “Cy,
                        J.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-06-02">June 2, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
                <p>3. <hi rend="italic">India:</hi> Regarding your comment on <persName
                        corresp="#p_CW_1">Warren Christopher</persName>’s May 31 evening report on
                    the Indian nuclear question,<note n="2" xml:id="d77fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d76fn6">footnote 6, Document 76</ref>.</note> I believe we
                    ought to reply to <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName> and tell him we
                    welcome the assurances which he conveyed to <persName corresp="#p_GRF_1">Bob
                        Goheen</persName> on <gloss target="#t_IAEA_1">IAEA</gloss> safeguards,
                    non-use of U.S. material in nuclear testing, and India’s willingness to
                    negotiate Tarapur and other non-proliferation issues. We should also welcome
                        <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName>’s assertion that he plans no
                    further nuclear tests and would consult with us if he changes his mind. This
                    message could be contained in a letter from you which replies to his May 16
                        letter.<note n="3" xml:id="d77fn3">See <ref target="#d73">Document
                        73</ref>.</note> Since <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName>’s letter
                    dealt at great length on the nuclear issue, it would be logical for your
                    response to develop this issue further. I will send you a draft shortly.<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d77fn4">In left-hand margin next to this paragraph, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “ok—be specific.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
            </div>
